  order: 3
---

Nominal has several primitives that are referenced throughout the platform and may already be familiar to test engineers. 
Together, these primitives make up Nominal's data model.

# Primitives

## Data sources

Nominal integrates various data sources, including:

- Relational and time-series databases (e.g., InfluxDB, TimeseriesDB, Nominal's native datastore)
- Cloud storage services (e.g., S3)
- Log files, weather data, and tabular datasets (e.g., CSV, Parquet)

Data can also be ingested with Nominal's [Python SDK](https://docs.nominal.io/python/quickstart).
For example, here is a [guide](https://docs.nominal.io/python/datasets/csv-files) for CSV file ingest with Python and Nominal. 

<Note>
    *Datasets* are the file representation of Nominal's *Data Source* primitive. 
    Most often, Datasets are tabular files with at least one time dimension.
    Datasets can also be video files.

    Head over to the [Datasets page](https://app.gov.nominal.io/data-sources?sidebar=allDatasets)
    to see your organization's most recently uploaded Datasets.
</Note>

## Channels 

Also know as *Series*.

A channel is a single column in a tabular Dataset or Data Source.
Channels are also often referred to as *"Series"* on the Nominal platform.

Nominal has 3 channel (or "series") types:

- **Numeric** - a series of points with a timestamp and a value.
- **Range** - a series of ranges defined by a condition (such as "voltage > 10"). Each range has a start and an end time.
- **Derived** - either a numeric series or a range series that was derived using a transform.
  - As of this writing (Nov. 2024), all range series are derived. In 2025, direct ingest of range series will be supported.

## Runs

Runs organize a collection of time series data under a common start and end time.

For example, for an engine firing test, you may collect a video and several sensor channels from various DAQ boards.

To associate this data with the same engine fire test, you would upload it to the same Run in Nominal.

<Note>
    In Nominal, *Runs* are containers of multimodal test data - including *Datasets*, *Videos*, *Logs*, and database connections.

    To see your organization's latest Runs, head over to the [Runs page](https://app.gov.nominal.io/runs) 
</Note>

## Assets

*(Coming Winter 2024)*

Assets are the device or system under test.

Assets can be any hardware. Examples of Assets include aircraft, drones, reactors, satellites, ground stations, robotics fleets, etc.

When the Assets feature is released, it will be possible to organize and retrieve Run data by an Asset identifier.

## Checks

Checks are rules applied to Run data. Usually, checks define nominal performance for the Asset under test. 
A collection of checks that can be applied to any run is a **Checklist**.

For example, you may create a Check that triggers an alert when a channel exceeds a certain scalar (eg a "first order check").

Checks can also be composed with multiple channels and higher order math. 
For example, you may write a rule-based check to calculate the RMS (root-mean-square) of 3 acceleration channels, then compare this to a baseline.
As another example, you may write a check that takes the difference between two channels
(say a simulation benchmark and its real-world data), then triggers an alert if the absolute value of their difference exceeds a certain floor. 

When Checks trigger their rule conditions, they issue Violation(s).

## Violations

A Violation is an instance of failure for a check applied to a run. 
A check can produce multiple violations in the same run. 
Engineers **Review** violations by making a disposition decision such as ‚ÄúIgnore‚Äù or ‚ÄúRequires further action.‚Äù

# Diagram

Nominal's data model can be visualized as the relationship between its primitives:

![data-model](https://res.cloudinary.com/didkpxvqu/image/upload/v1729634194/nominal-data-model-q4_qczgnd.svg)

# Glossary

In addition to the core primitives defined above, you may encounter these terms in the Nominal platform.

## Workbooks

Workbooks are Nominal's no-code dashboarding and computation environment.
They are most often used for ad hoc and root cause analysis (RCA) on Run data. 
When anomalies are identied in Workbooks, they can be saved as Checks that automatically trigger alerts when the anomaly reappears in future Runs.
Workbook layouts can be templatized and applied to multiple Runs.

## Ref name

<Note>
Ref names (reference names) are a namespace for data sources that share common channels, but do not necessarily belong to the same Run.
They allow data sources with similar schema to be referenced as a group. For example, data sources with the same ref name can share 
Workbook templates and Checklists.
</Note>

## Resource ID

<Note>
    All Nominal primitives (eg Datasets, Runs, Workbooks, and Checks) have a unique identifier called a "Resource ID".
    Resource IDs may be referred to as "RID" or simply "ID" throughout the platform. They can be obtained from
    a primitive's detail page (or URL) and have a format that looks like `ri.catalog.cerulean-staging.dataset.e5ede17b-05f9-404d-aaf5-ba85c99761a2`.
</Note>

docs/pages/guides/platform/weather-conne.markdown:
---
title: Weather
description: >-
  Connecting to the NOAA weather database on Nominal - the test platform for
  teams developing advanced hardware
sidebar:
  order: 2
---

In addition to data files, log files, videos, cloud data stores, and databases, 
Nominal can set up a weather connection to fetch current weather data for any location.

To learn about data sources other than weather live streaming, please reference the 
[Data sources](/platform/guide/getting-started/data-model#data-sources) section of the 
[Data model](http://localhost:3000/platform/guide/getting-started/data-model) page.

# FAQ

## How can I access weather data?
    
Contact a Nominal engineer to set up a weather connection for your organization.  Once set up, everyone in your organization will have access to weather as a data connection, available in *Data sources* ‚Üí *Connections*.  After setup, you can add weather to a run as an additional data source.
    
## What weather data does Nominal provide?
    
Nominal provides numeric channel data on:

- real temperature (live)
- dew point
- relative humidity
- wind speed 10, 50, 80, and 100 meters above ground level
- wind gust at 10 meters above ground level
- wind direction at 10, 50, 80, and 100 meters above ground level
- wind chill at 10 meters above ground level
- visibility
- cloud coverage
- sea level pressure
- heat index (when available)
- precipitation (when available)
- precipitation coverage (when available)
- snow depth (when available)
- wave height
- wave direction
- wave crest period
- swell height
- swell direction
- swell crest period
    
Nominal also provides categorical data on weather conditions (i.e. ‚ÄúPartially cloudy‚Äù).
    
## Where does the weather data come from?
    
Nominal uses the [Visual Crossing](https://www.visualcrossing.com/) weather API for data.
Visual Crossing receives data from ground-based weather stations, satellites, and radar. 
They weight results from ground stations more strongly due to their higher accuracy.  
To do this, they [rely on both NOAA stations and non-NOAA stations](https://www.visualcrossing.com/resources/documentation/weather-data/weather-data-sources-and-attribution/).

Measurements are generally at or near ground level unless otherwise indicated.

Nominal sources weather data from up to 3 weather stations near to the requested location, weighted by distance to the desired spot. 
Nominal obfuscates the originator of all requests made to Visual Crossing, so weather data queries are not associated with your organization. 
    
## How recent is the data?
    
Data will generally be available up until the last hour, regardless of when you view it.
    
## What units are the data in?
    
All data is in metric units.  You can view the units for a specific channel by navigating in Nominal to *Data sources ‚Üí Connections*, then selecting the weather connection.  
    
In a Workbook, you can change the units on a channel by clicking the **Transform** button on the channel in the chart legend, and selecting **Unit conversion**.
    
## How often is the data queried?
    
Nominal provides weather estimates at 5 minute intervals.  For some channels (specifically wave data, swell data, and wind data at 50 meters and higher), 
Nominal can only provide data at hourly intervals.

docs/pages/guides/platform/workbooks/cre.markdown:
---
title: Creating a workbook
description: How to create a Nominal Workbook for ad hoc test data discovery and analysis.
sidebar:
  order: 10
---

![Untitled](<file:8960b1b0-a9be-482a-8d26-d4e2d69148ec>)

The details page for each run contains several tabs, the first of which is a list of **published workbooks** for that run, created by users within the organization. 

Clicking the **New workbook** button in the top right of this page will open a new workbook tied to this run. Once published, the new workbook becomes accessible any user in the organization from the run page.

### Workbooks are artifacts of exploration

**Workbooks are artifacts of exploration for a single run**, so you cannot swap runs directly in a workbook. If you want to apply the charts you build in a workbook to another run, you have two options:

1. [Create a template from a workbook](/platform/guide/workbooks/creating-a-workbook#create-a-template-from-a-workbook) 
2. [Duplicate a workbook with a new run ](/platform/guide/workbooks/creating-a-workbook#duplicate-a-workbook-with-a-new-run) 

For right now, we‚Äôll focus on exploration of a single run, then cover analysis across runs using templates.

## Adding channels

![Untitled](file:42d81999-4cb9-4a0e-9de5-575d7ea52be9)

A new workbook starts with a single empty chart on a single tab. To get started, add some channels from a run. 

Click the **Add Channels** button in the left sidebar to open the channel selector. It is populated with all the time series in the run‚Äôs data sources. Select the desired channels and add them to the chart.

![Untitled](<file:6b0c913f-c896-4e88-b9a3-bbfd8074e0bf>)

After more channels are added, the large **Add Channels** button is replaced by a plus (+) button in the top right corner of the left-hand chart legend. 



If the data is organized hierarchically, it can be browsed in a hierarchical view. To toggle between this view and the list view, click the button in the upper right hand corner of the modal. 



![Untitled](file:3b112539-4d63-4dc2-8834-e863fcaa73cd)

## Arranging channels

When an additional set of channels is added as described above, they will appear on a new row in the chart. Rows can be rearranged using the options menu next to each channel in the legend.

You can also click the plus (+) on a row to add a channel to that specific row. 

![Untitled](file:922f43db-1e81-4f52-9e57-a291e04aaa43)

Rows can included multiple overlaid axes, which can be rearranged from the options menu. Additional customization options available include color, line style, channel name, and duplicating channel.

## Zooming and scaling time series charts

Time series charts consistently plot time on the X axis and the channel value on the Y axis, referred to as the **time axis** and **value axis** respectively. These axes possess the following properties:

- Charts have one time axis, and one or more value axes.
- It is possible to overlay multiple axes on a single chart.
- Rows within charts have at least one value axis.

[https://www.loom.com/share/e1353f7cfbe84c18aab29d96d2ea5878](https://www.loom.com/share/e1353f7cfbe84c18aab29d96d2ea5878)

The video above shows some basic ways to navigate around Nominal charts:

- **Hold shift and drag to zoom** to a narrower time window. Does not affect zoom level on the value axis.
- Click **Reset time (**at the top of the workbook) to see the whole run at once
- Use the **top-left chart controls** to adjust the **value axis**: zoom in, zoom out, and reset
- Use the **bottom-right chart controls** as another way to adjust the time axis
- **Hover** **over any point** to see the values of all plotted channels at that time

![Untitled](<file:b8bf8830-4a67-40ff-bb2b-a6bd097b3923>)

Nominal also enables the offsetting of axes within the same chart and the same row. The video below demonstrates how to **click and drag on axis labels** to adjust offset within a chart row.

[https://www.loom.com/share/db96612851af47da92ea989d84ef9837](https://www.loom.com/share/db96612851af47da92ea989d84ef9837)

Additionally, the video illustrates how to change the default range of an axis. To do this, open the options menu for the axis in the legend, select **Default range**, and apply changes. The axis will be set to those bounds and will reset to those bounds whenever the **Reset axis** button in the top left chart controls is activated.

## Transforming channels

Much of the computational power of Nominal lies in the transform tool, which facilitates point-and-click transformations of time series channels. To access the transform tool, click the **Triangle icon** to the right of any channel in the legend list.

![Untitled](<file:95212da6-aa2d-40c5-8430-992cb592418b>)

From here, there is an option to either create a new derived channel (‚ÄùCreate from‚Äù) or modify your current channel (‚ÄùApply to‚Äù). Both options offer the same choice of transformations. Within each, multiple types of transformations are available:

- **Numeric** and **enum transformations** produce derived time series with the same sampling as the source channel.
- **Range transformations** produce ranges of time that meet a given condition

![Untitled](<file:369fa231-9f5d-4417-ade3-610f15e3adb6>)

After selecting the desired transformation and filling out any necessary fields, apply the changes. The newly transformed channel will appear in the chart legend.

To edit the transformation later, click the options menu to the left of the transform name, which will reopen the initial configuration menu for the transform. 

To remove (or ‚Äúpop‚Äù) the transform, click the minus side to the right of the transform name. If several transformations are applied, only the last transformation will be removed.

## Building formulas

All channels loaded in a workbook are provided an algebraic variable name (e.g. `a`, `b`, `c`), which can be used to define derived channels using more expressive formulas.

To create a formula, click the **Add formula** button to the left of **Add channels** in the chart legend. A formula builder will appear. On the left, define the formula‚Äôs name and expression. On the right,  a **reference list** displays all channels along with their algebraic variable names.

In the example below, we average two battery temperature fields to produce a third one.

![Untitled](<file:e515948d-cf65-491f-8e04-2aef93cd67c2>)

The table beneath the formula editor shows the operations you can apply to formulas, and the syntax to do so.

## Stacking transforms

Transforms can be built on raw series, formulas, and other transforms. Stacked transforms are accessible by clicking the triangular transform icon located on the channel row in the chart legend.

![Untitled](<file:3604bc5c-9aca-4441-9b20-9a786241dbe1>)

Any transform in the stack can be edited. After applying changes, the selected transform and all subsequent transforms in the stack will recompute.

Additionally, any transform can be removed from the stack by clicking the minus button to its right.

## Comparing with other runs

A workbook is tied to a single primary run, but it allows for comparison with other runs on a channel-by-channel basis. To initiate a comparison, open the run comparison panel in the chart legend, and select the runs you wish to compare. 

![Untitled](<file:5be8819a-ced7-4a59-83b0-472202ea9ec6>)

The comparison runs will be displayed as faintly-colored channels of the same hue as workbook run‚Äôs channel. To align the runs for accurate comparison, adjust the offset in the comparison run editor to line up the two runs at the desired moment.

![Untitled](file:3f6acd47-ccd2-42e5-9dc0-21c5a6139ab5)

Multiple sets of comparison runs can be added, and runs can be hidden or shown for comparison as needed. 

However, if the chart has too many channels, or if too many runs are compared simultaneously, it can become cluttered. Run comparison is most effective when limited to comparing 1-2 channels among a small number of runs.

## Using event annotations

Clicking on the graph opens the option to add an event, marking that point in time.

![Untitled](<file:70d31a02-721c-4baf-8f05-d952a8f665ec>)

![Untitled](<file:3a0a3115-c53e-4740-ae50-22011feabf1e>)

After selecting **Add event,** provide a name and specify the level (info, flag, error, or success). These indications appear on the graph as vertical lines, colored by their flag type.

![Untitled](file:4c518d37-ba59-4ae2-ba0b-7949a7856206)

In the bottom drawer of the workbook, navigate to the events tab to see the list of all created events. From here, you can adjust an event‚Äôs visibility, change its name, delete it, or designate it as the t-0 of the entire run.

![Untitled](<file:0061e2e4-e60f-4282-a54a-1e5ef5e39c40>)

> ‚ö†Ô∏è¬†Setting an event as t-0 for an entire run has implications across other workbooks that use this run. Only do so carefully! ‚ö†Ô∏è
> 

## Using run logs

If logs were added to your run during its creation, they can be viewed in the bottom drawer of a workbook associated with that run. This drawer supports searching and filtering by log message and timestamp.

![Untitled](<file:c491f721-b49b-4966-b666-d65e13e5a396>)

## Publishing a workbook

All workbooks are instantiated in **private mode**, meaning they are visible only to the creator. To make a workbook accessible to others, it must be published. The private-to-published toggle is in the upper right of the workbook. Selecting **Published** will make the workbook visible to the entire organization.

![Untitled](<file:76cf580c-9b83-4082-8599-0b15648e4852>)

## Create a template from a workbook

To create a template from an existing workbook, select the options menu at the top right of the workbook, and select the **Create a template** option. Templates are run-agnostic, which means you can apply your workbook setup to other runs. 

![Untitled](<file:df5f3d4b-27a3-4cac-9762-553af8e891e9>)

## Duplicate a workbook with a new run

Another method for re-using a workbook is to duplicate it, also available from the same menu. Duplicating a workbook does not create a template; instead, it creates another workbook to be attached to a different run.

## Exporting a workbook

All time series charts are exportable to a `csv` format, with a maximum export size of 2gb.

Channels from the original data source, as well as transformations resulting in a numeric or enum channel are all supported. Cartesian charts and range channels cannot be exported.

![Untitled](<file:d5538eea-2ec8-48f7-a1a5-e6b832c55efb>)

To begin, click the 3-dot menu in the upper right corner of a chart and select **Export to CSV**. The following modal will appear, offering a range of export options.

![Untitled](file:f55ee4b7-1716-492a-b8fb-fea77f09ccf8)

### Time series export options

Exporting time series data presents the following configuration options:

- **Time range**: ****Defaults to the range currently in view
- **Timestamp format**: ISO-8601 and relative timestamps are both supported
- **Timestamp resolution**: For now, only a raw resolution is supported. The export will use all timestamps present in the original run within the configured time range
- **Timestamp fill strategy**: How you would like the export to handle empty values in a channel
    - **None**: Empty values will export as empty values
    - **Forward fill**: The last known value will be carried forward to subsequent timestamps. If configured with a lookback time limit, the export will revert to using empty values when that time limit has been reached since the last known value. If no limit is set, values will be carried forward for the remainder of the file or until a non-empty value is reached.
- **GZip**: If checked, will export as a zipped `.csv.gz` file. Otherwise, will export as a plain `.csv`
    - Note: OS default archive utilities may not be able to decompress the exported gzip. If you run into that problem, try the [gunzip](https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/gunzip-command-in-linux-with-examples/) utility or another tool.

When ready, click **Download** and your export will begin in a new tab.

---

docs/pages/guides/platform/workbooks/mul.markdown:
---
title: Multimodal panels
description: >-
  Nominal Workbooks accommodate a wide range of panel types for data
  visualization and analysis.
sidebar:
  order: 13
---

In addition to time series charts, Nominal workbooks also support:

- üé¨ Time-synchronized video with playback
- Scatter plots
- üåé¬†Geographic trace plots
- üìä¬†Histograms for any numeric time series
- Fourier transform plots for any numeric time series

The following sections demonstrate how to create and use these new chart types. 

Additionally, the documentation covers how these panels share a **common playhead**, so that a moment of time is consistently in focus across video, time series charts, scatter plots, and geographic traces.

## Time-synced video

A video panel can now be added to an existing workbook. When the video is played, the playhead moves across any time series charts that have been added, synchronizing the video with the data visualization.

![Untitled](<file:fcb1c647-a963-4b60-affb-526980b2ffb2>)

### Adding a video to a workbook

![Untitled](<file:82c23a4c-0a68-4f96-9ce4-5436ec61593e>)

After a video is linked to a run, it can be added to any workbook for that run. Open a workbook for a video run and add a new panel. 

A variety of panel types are available, including time series, histogram, and video panel. Select **Add video panel**, then select the file linked to the run. Upon selection, a video player should load.

### Video playback

From this point, the video can be played back in synchronization with the time series data. After adding the video, a purple vertical playhead line will appear on any time series chart, indicating the time location where the video starts. 

![Untitled](<file:5ea66103-e517-40ec-b393-9b170073eb1f>)

Press **play** either on the video, or using the **Play button** at the top of the workbook, to the left of the centered time range viewer. As the video plays, the playhead follows along the time series chart. 

### Moving the video playhead

The video playhead can be moved by clicking or scrubbing on the timeline in the video player. 

When the video is clicked or dragged to a new time location, the playhead will snap to this new time across all other charts, ensuring synchronization.

![Untitled](<file:fc3d6870-5710-455d-93f6-b67473580d07>)

![Untitled](<file:0c5a3e54-595d-417d-a1ec-112dfd28e95b>)

If zoomed in on a time series chart, and the playhead is outside the view window, a button appears in the top right or top left of the chart, to advance or rewind the chart to the playhead.

### Using the playhead in other charts

In addition to the vertical line on time series, the playhead manifests on scatter plots and geo plots as a highlighted point in time. In the screenshot below, both a scatter plot (top right) and geo plot (bottom right) show crosshairs marking the location of the playhead on those plots.

![Untitled](<file:aa72148c-c327-4f7e-9a58-4331e58deb4f>)

## Scatter plots

### Creating scatter plots

To create a scatter plot, select the ‚Äúscatter plot‚Äù option from the new tab dropdown menu, and select the two time series you wish to represent X and Y. Select from any time series present in any chart in the workbook. The scatter plot will open in a new tab.

[https://www.loom.com/share/d6b88ac200ba4684acc5e50a2ecec05b](https://www.loom.com/share/d6b88ac200ba4684acc5e50a2ecec05b)

### Replacing channels in a scatter plot

After creating a scatter plot, the X or Y channel can be swapped for another time series in the workbook. Hover over the X or Y channel in the legend, open the options menu, and select ‚ÄúReplace Channel‚Äù.

![Untitled](<file:2eff5986-3476-4fe5-9c27-4555043f84e2>)

### Modifying channels in a scatter plot

The data visualized by the scatter plot is controlled by the ‚Äúsource‚Äù time series selected for the X and Y channels. Any additions or modifications to transforms on those source channels in their respective time series graphs will be reflected in the scatter plot.

[https://www.loom.com/share/aeed0c98be8a4d02a12324676f33e843](https://www.loom.com/share/aeed0c98be8a4d02a12324676f33e843)

### Updating time range

Currently, all charts in a workbook share the same time range; updating the time range on any chart will simultaneously update it on every other chart, including scatter plots. To change the time range over which a scatter plot reports data, select the desired range in a time series chart.

### Bucketing and decimation

Scatter plots display up to 10,000 points on the screen at any given time. If the visible range of data contains more than 10,000 points, some nearby points will be bucketed together. 

Single points appear as **circles** on the plot, and bucketed points appear as lightly-shaded **boxes** that form the bounding box of all the points contained within. 

Hover over a point or a bucket to get more information. Hovering on a bucket shows how many points it contains.

[https://www.loom.com/share/860e517d508b46088b0d473799c9ff62](https://www.loom.com/share/860e517d508b46088b0d473799c9ff62)

## Geographic maps

Nominal workbooks support geographic plots that trace the latitude and longitude channels of a time series data source, and draw the trace over a real-world map. 

In the screenshot above, the bottom right geo plot shows a plane executing a spiral maneuver over terrain.

### Adding a geo map to a workbook

To use a geo plot in a workbook, ensure that the workbook is linked to a run that has two time series channels representing latitude and longitude respectively. 

- Latitude values must be between -90 and +90
- Longitude values must be between -180 and +180

From any **empty panel** in the workbook, or from the panel button in the top right of the workbook, select **Add geo map** from the list. 

![Untitled](<file:9d10fb37-a82f-4962-9ef6-fc42a69d43bb>)

![Untitled](<file:2f33f824-5962-49c9-b797-95ebb826c794>)

When adding a new geo panel to a workbook, a blank map of the world appears, along with buttons in the left-hand legend to select latitude and longitude.

Once both channels are selected, the map will automatically zoom to the bounding box of the path drawn by the latitude and longitude channels.

Hovering on a geo map draws a line from your cursor to the nearest point along the trace, and displays the latitude, longitude, and timestamp in the top left of the map.

![Untitled](<file:594c5432-4c71-49a0-8dd2-45a33dd43441>)

### Zoom on a geo map

Playing a video or moving the playhead refocuses the geo map to the observation window of the viewable time range. Drag-zooming on the geo map allows focusing on a specific portion of the lat/long trace. To relinquish control back to the playhead, click the reset button in the upper right-hand corner of the map.

Zooming in on a time series chart restricts the observation window of the geo plot (and all other charts) to that specific time range. Consequently, the geo plot zooms in to focus on the lat/long trace within that time range. A lower opacity line remains visible in the background, representing the full bounds of the data at a reduced sampling rate.

### Using the playhead

On playback, coordinate point at the playhead‚Äôs timestamp is highlighted along the trace, and stays updated as playback continues. 

## Histograms

Nominal workbooks also support histograms, which can immediately plot the value distribution of any numeric time series channel. 

### Adding a histogram to a workbook

To create a histogram, select **Add histogram panel** from the add panel menu, and add a time series channel to see its distribution.

Hover over any channel bucket on the chart to see the count of values in that bucket, and the bucket‚Äôs bounding range.

![Untitled](<file:dde96e22-a2f2-40a8-982f-ed5915c509bc>)

![Untitled](<file:1f26d4ae-b556-4880-8b78-44c221a0a5e8>)

You can add multiple time series channels to a histogram, and those channels will share buckets. These channel buckets can be grouped (default, shown on left) or stacked (shown on right).

### Using bucket strategy

By default, each time series is divided into 10 buckets of equal value width. The first bucket will either start at zero or start at a value that is a multiple of the bucket width, so that the histogram is zero-aligned.

If you want to see distribution using a different bucket strategy, there are two options:

1. Set the **bucket count**, defining the exact number of buckets returned
2. Set the **bucket width**, defining the size of each bucket‚Äôs bounding range

Both of these strategies align buckets at zero, the same as the default strategy. 

### Using bucket width + offset

When setting the bucket width in a histogram, an optional offset value can be added, which shifts the alignment rightwards by the specified amount. The offset must be a positive value.

![Untitled](<file:1612cd8d-4743-4b61-b55c-27fbe19a45dd>)

The screenshot above shows the same histogram as before, with a custom width (1000) and offset (500). The first bucket is now aligned to range [-500, +500], rather than starting at zero.

## Fourier transforms

To support analysis of time-varying signals, Nominal workbooks now support frequency-domain charts that plot Fourier transforms of numeric time series.

### Adding a frequency chart

To create a frequency chart, select **Add frequency panel** from the add panel menu, and add a time series channel to see its Fourier transform.

The function accepts any channel that represents a time-varying signal, and automatically computes a fast Fourier transform. 

The FFT does not apply any windowing function or normalization. For best results, apply FFTs to time series channels with constant sampling rates.

### FFT window size

The FFT window includes all the points in workbook‚Äôs time range, which is controlled by zooming and resetting a time series chart. 

![Untitled](<file:0c34d01a-f28a-47c2-b178-36f9650461be>)

This window must be narrow enough to compute an FFT efficiently. If the window contains more than 10,000 points, the chart will display a message saying that the window is too large.x

![Untitled](<file:c4cdea37-ed78-4950-98d3-b553670b0ce1>)

To narrow the window, pull up a time series chart alongside the frequency chart, and shift-drag on a range that shows the time-varying signal to analyze.

---

docs/pages/guides/platform/workbooks/usi.markdown: --- title: Using templates description: Standardize popular Workbook formats with Templates. sidebar: order: 12 --- ## Workbooks vs workbook templates The two main differences between workbooks and workbook templates are: 1. **Workbooks are tied to a specific run, while templates are not.** When runs are swapped in a template, all channels reload, all channel transforms and formulas recompute, and all charts re-render automatically. 2. **Published templates are read-only by default, while workbooks are editable by default.** To edit a template, create a new draft and publish that draft. See more in the [Viewing and editing a published template](#viewing-and-editing-a-published-template) section. ## Creating a template To create a template, you can either [Create a template from a workbook](/platform/guide/workbooks/creating-a-workbook#create-a-template-from-a-workbook) or create a new template from scratch from the [workbooks](https://app.gov.nominal.io/workbooks) page. Click the **New template (Beta)** button at the top right of the screen. ![Screenshot 2024-03-06 at 8.25.38 AM.png](file:8d488adf-790a-400f-9857-25af362b5d91) Initially, a title and description must be added, aiding in organizing draft templates before publication. The template will be created in draft mode, and you can publish whenever you like. ![Untitled]() ## Selecting a reference run Although workbook templates are independent of runs, plotting data and observing how the template applies to a particular run is still necessary. To begin, select a reference run, which provides a list of channels and their underlying time series data for use in plotting, transformation, and formula building. ![Untitled]() ## Swapping runs in a template Upon selecting a reference run, users are directed to a workbook where they can begin constructing charts. Charts within the template are tied to specific **channels** initially selected from your reference run. The chart can be used on any run that contains the referenced channel, or in the case of a channel transform or formula, the raw channels that ultimately back the computed channel. To swap runs in a template and see how a chart changes, click the run indicator at the top of the workbook template, and select a new run. Runs can be swapped as often as needed. ![Untitled]() ## Publishing a template Before publishing a template for others in the organization to see, you‚Äôll see it in the **Not published** section of the workbook index. [Click here](https://app.gov.nominal.io/workbooks?sidebar=notPublishedTemplates) to open the page. ![Untitled]() For a template to be visible and usable by others, it needs to be published. After creating the desired charts, the template can be published by using the **Publish** button in the top right. ## Viewing and editing a published template Published templates are read-only when opened. If changes are needed, click the **Edit Template** button. Changes to templates are saved automatically in a draft state and won't be published until they are finalized. To begin, assign a name to the draft. ![Untitled](file:b9b41bd4-d0fa-4ab4-81d5-57abe02949fb) Once a draft is created, it can be edited extensively, with changes automatically saving to the current draft. ![Untitled]() There are two ways to publish a draft: - Publish as a **new version** overwrites the current template - Publish as a **new template** creates a copy If you leave Nominal before publishing your draft, you can return to it by navigating to the published template and clicking **Edit Template** again. This will present the option to edit an existing draft. Note that you can only view and edit your own drafts. ![Screenshot 2024-03-07 at 1.31.18 PM.png](file:90d72d58-c48e-4c7d-857f-07b41290ab48) ## Adding charts from a template to a workbook If you have a template you like, you can add the charts in that template as new tabs in any workbook. To do so, open a workbook and click the add tab button. Select the **Add panels from template** option, then select the template whose charts you wish to pull in. ![Untitled]() After selecting a template, new tabs containing all the charts from the source template will appear in your workbook, applied to the data of your workbook‚Äôs run. ![Untitled](file:6e1bbc65-52d1-4ce1-a5bc-86ee5b6b33ec) ---

docs/pages/guides/platform/creating-runs.markdown: --- title: Creating runs description: >- How to instantiate Runs on Nominal. Runs test data defined by a time domain of interest. sidebar: order: 4 --- ## Managing data sources and channels A data source can be either a database connection or an uploaded file; in either case the data source records must contain timestamps. Files can be uploaded through the application user interface (we currently support CSV and video upload). Reach out to the Nominal team for help connecting to your databases (we currently support InfluxDB and TimescaleDB). ## Uploading a CSV To upload a CSV to use as a data source, navigate to the runs page of the app ([runs page](https://app.gov.nominal.io/runs)), and click **Upload CSVs.** A file selector will open, allowing the selection of one or more CSVs from a file system. ![Untitled]() Once selected, a preview of the parsed rows and columns will be displayed. On this form, it is possible to name the data source, select which column to use as the timestamp, and specify its format. CSVs may contain relative or absolute time. ![Untitled](file:6191d8e7-6081-4adf-8cf1-a70ed5d3f66f) Nominal accepts three timestamp formats: - Absolute (ISO-8601): A time stamp with time zone. Formatted like `2024-03-06T04:55:14Z` - Absolute (Unix Time): A numeric value representing time elapsed since epoch. Example: `1709833562194` - Allowed units: Hours, minutes, seconds, milliseconds, microseconds, or nanoseconds - Relative: A numeric value. Assumes that t = 0 is the start time of the data source. - Allowed units: Hours, minutes, seconds, milliseconds, microseconds, or nanoseconds Once ready, upload the file. When it‚Äôs done uploading, it will be available in the data sources list in the run creation form. ## Uploading a video To upload a video from your computer, navigate to the data sources tab ([https://app.gov.nominal.io/data-sources](https://app.gov.nominal.io/data-sources)) and select the **Upload data** button on the top right of the page, then **Upload videos**. A file selector opens, enabling the selection of one or more videos to upload. ![Untitled]() Any video file uploaded should be a `.mp4` , `.mov`, or `.avi` file, using the h.265 codec. Once selected, set the UTC (not local time zone) start time of the video. *This step is important,* as the start time chosen here synchronizes the video with the run it will be linked to. ![Untitled]() ### Linking a video to a run Once a video has been uploaded as a data source, it can be linked to a new or existing run, so that it can be used in workbooks. **Linking to an existing run** If attaching a video to an existing run, navigate to that run‚Äôs details page (select the desired run in the list at [https://app.gov.nominal.io/runs](https://app.gov.nominal.io/runs)). ![Untitled]() Once on the run details page, select the **Data sources** tab at underneath the run title, and click the **Add data source** button. Then select the uploaded video from the dropdown. ![Untitled]() To link the video to a run, it is necessary to use a ‚Äúref name‚Äù ‚Äî a shorthand way of referring to the video data source in-app, for example ‚Äòcockpit_video‚Äô. **Linking to a new run** When creating a new run that requires linking a video, this video can be added as a data source during the run creation process. For detailed instructions on creating a run, refer to the documentation in the user manual: [Creating a run](/platform/guide/runs-and-checks/creating-runs) ![Untitled](file:1bf8e90c-541e-4520-8f37-3fe4c9d42001) In the data sources section of the run creation form, select **Video file** and add an uploaded video from the dropdown list. The video *must be uploaded prior to attachment*. If the video has not yet been uploaded, the run can still be created, and the video can be added later via the run details page. ## Dedicated data sources page A list of all data sources is accessible from the tab at the top of the left sidebar. If videos have been uploaded to Nominal, they‚Äôre also accessible from this page. ![Untitled]() From here, clicking into any data source reveals metadata and channel information. Each data source displays a list of channels, each capable of being loaded into a workbook or validated using a checklist. ![Untitled]() Each channel can be annotated with a unit of measurement and a description. Providing a unit of measurement ensures the channel adheres to the rules described in the [üìê¬†Units & dimensional analysis](https://nmnl.notion.site/What-s-new-37e53873e727441dbb7d73504123361f#634cf6589b8748829c31a4aaac0fe12c) section below. On the right hand side of the data source page, users can modify its labels and properties. ## üå≤¬†Channel tree view When connecting or uploading a data source, Nominal gathers metadata about channels in that data source. **Delimiters** in channel names can be used to automatically create a hierarchy for those channels. This channel hierarchy is reflected in the channel selection interface for workbooks and validation rules. This selector shows a tree view of the channels in a data source, and provides quick multi-select for all the channels nested under a single parent. ![Untitled](file:82d74dd1-cc7f-4f89-be0e-6bfce93288f4) ### Hierarchical delimiters in channel names When uploading a file, a choice of what delimiter is available: *period, hyphen, underscore, or pipe*. ![Untitled]() For example, if a data source includes channels named `vehicle.engine.temperature` and `vehicle.engine.rpm`, selecting `Period` as the delimiter will place `vehicle`, `engine`, and `temperature` on different levels of the hierarchy, with `temperature` and `rpm` at the same level under `engine`. The channel tree view shows this hierarchy. It is accessible on the data sources page, and on the channel selector in workbooks and checklists. [https://www.loom.com/share/c80ccb6b99fa45d0a402f14445845e78](https://www.loom.com/share/c80ccb6b99fa45d0a402f14445845e78) ## üìê¬†Units & dimensional analysis Time series data can represent all sorts of real-world measurements, such as pressure, temperature, or voltage over time. In Nominal, the unit of measurement for any channel can be set or changed, ensuring that volts are treated as volts, and meters are not mistaken for feet. ![Untitled]() The unit of any channel can be set by opening the page for the channel‚Äôs data source, selecting the channel, and setting its **Unit of measurement** from a dropdown list. ### Operations with units Operations on channels in workbooks and checklists respect their units, meaning: - Units appear alongside channel names and on plotted axes - Different units plotted on the same axes will generate warnings ![Screenshot 2024-06-18 at 5.56.17‚ÄØPM.png](file:12eef177-c5cb-496a-a69d-f22460f4b3af) - Derived channels that involve incompatible unit operations will also generate warnings, providing safeguarding against potential computation errors‚Äî for example, adding a series measured in meters to one measured in centimeters, or comparing values of a series measured in seconds to a series measured in degrees. ![Screenshot 2024-06-18 at 5.57.19‚ÄØPM.png](file:25a68b7c-fdd0-4a12-b4c8-def72896dc67) - Derived channels will automatically convert their units whenever possible. For example, taking the derivative of a series measuring speed will return a series with a unit of acceleration. ### Unit conversion transform Nominal supports unit conversion as a transform function on channels with units defined. If a unit of measurement has multiple possible unit types, such as angles being degrees or radians, the transformation converts values of one type to the other. ![Untitled]() ## Creating a run Once data sources are added, creating a run is possible by filling out a few points of configuration. ### Required fields - **Run name:** should be unique among runs - **Data sources:** CSVs (relative- or absolute-time), and/or database connections - **Time offset** - By default, all CSVs are aligned to the start time of the run, t=0 - Use the **Time offset** field to offset from t=0 in seconds - Absolute-time data sources, however, are automatically time synced - **Ref name** - Use a common ref name for data sources that contain channels with the same names - **Time range:** the start and end date time of the run in UTC; ensure this is consistent with the bounds of the time ranges on data sources Data source fields are editable once added. Data source selection, ref name, and offset are all accessible through the edit menu. ![Untitled]() ### Optional fields - **Properties:** key-value pairs for searching and filtering runs. - Properties are most appropriate for key-value pairs where the key should be present across most or all runs - **Labels:** keywords for searching and filtering runs - Labels are appropriate when the category will not be present on most runs - **Logs:** files that add context, containing rows of valid timestamps and messages. Logs must be `\n` line-delimited text files with `.txt` or `.log` extensions. - The string before the first whitespace is parsed as an ISO-8601 time stamp - The rest of the line is treated as the log message Runs can also be created via API and Python, for more details, see [Nominal Python documentation](https://docs.nominal.io/python/runs/overview). ---

docs/pages/guides/platform/using-checkli.markdown:
---
title: Using checklists
description: >-
  How to instantiate and use a Checklist on Nominal. Checks define test data
  that is off spec or "out of family." Checks can also trigger Violations to
  initiate a test data review.
sidebar:
  order: 5
---

## Checklists overview

We‚Äôve shown how to explore time series data in runs for ad-hoc analysis with workbooks. Nominal also gives you the ability to define and run checks against new runs. Nominal organizes checks into checklists, and allows you to apply a whole checklist to a run.

A checklist applied to a run will trigger violations over the time ranges that a check fails. A single check can fail multiple times during a run, producing multiple violations. 

To complete a data review of a run, decide for each check violation if it should be (a) **ignored** or (b) requires **further action.** 

## Creating a checklist

To create a new checklist, navigate to the checklists page on the app. You can [click here](https://app.gov.nominal.io/checks), or navigate via the checklist icon on the left-hand sidebar of the app. Once you‚Äôre on the checklists page, click **New checklist** in the top right to get started.

![Untitled](<file:5c9abc86-3cca-4c40-95ab-e410e606ea10>)

Checklists are untitled when you first create them. Add a name and description to help organize your checklists. Checklists are also empty on creation; you‚Äôll want to add some checks.

When you create a new checklist from the checklist page, you‚Äôll be asked to select a reference run, against which you can test the behavior of each check. Once you‚Äôve selected a reference run, you‚Äôll be prompted to create your first check.

![Untitled](<file:8fc04b22-00d5-432c-b976-f5cca1b6fcca>)

## ‚úèÔ∏è¬†Authoring a check

We've developed a more powerful way to author all the checks in your checklist from a single location. You can now define nested conditional logic, as well as promote those conditions to variables for use across other checks in the checklist.

### Adding your first check

When creating a new checklist, you‚Äôll be prompted to name your first check. Description and priority are optional.

![Untitled](<file:77871c8c-4082-495b-a0eb-f929c0ef2fa4>)

After clicking **Add check,**  the check logic can be built in the following ways:

- as a check on a single condition (e.g. `temperature < 1000`)
- as an `AND` or `OR` check on a list of conditions
- as an `AND` or `OR` check on nested conditions

### Defining a check from a single condition

 Start by defining a single condition. Select a channel, and then apply a value comparison to that channel. 

![Untitled](<file:83d93b91-8a1e-4f27-8e1c-0c4604480f9a>)

Select **Add channel from data source.** This brings up a list of all the channels in the reference run originally selected. As soon as  a channel is selected,  it appears in the preview area.

![Untitled](<file:4a9fc0ee-ffd8-40c2-9c56-fc81105685ab>)

From here, you can define a check that highlights a simple range of time. The example check below highlights whenever **speed_mph** exceeds 500. The violation range for the preview run is highlighted  red.

![Untitled](file:ec86f540-c3e3-424f-806d-2016c2ad9c23)

### ‚Ü™Ô∏è Inverting conditions

The drop-down at the top of the check definition allows you to select whether violations are highlighted when the condition ***is met*** (default) or ***is not met***.

![Untitled](<file:05bb8627-7758-43d2-ace1-dd768d045b26>)

### ‚ûï¬†Adding more conditions

Click the **Add condition** button on any check to add additional conditions. Conditions can be joined with **And** or **Or**. Each channel or variable added displays as a row in the check preview.

![Untitled](<file:1fbab896-2e1e-4d93-b943-27ed8702b44f>)

### üê¶¬†Nesting conditions

Click the **Add condition group** button to add a nested subgroup of conditions with their own logic. Like individual conditions, condition groups can be evaluated either using **And** or **Or**.

![Untitled](file:92fd31f7-b30b-4699-889a-10e0c1d48d9e)

## Using variables across checks

Nominal supports variables that can be used across checks. You can create variables from the menu in the bottom right of the checklist builder. 

![Untitled](<file:c65c43d2-08d5-4851-aeaf-b1f91d0d87a4>)

Variables can function as check **conditions** directly, or as **channels** or **custom formulas** whose values can be compared to thresholds to produce conditions used in checks. 

> *Note: When the definition of a variable condition changes, it changes in every check.*
> 

## üìà¬†Creating a channel variable

In this example, we‚Äôre going to create a variable to represent the rolling rate of climb for our aircraft, derived from an altitude time series channel in our data source. We click **Add channel from data source** and select our raw channel to start from.

![Untitled](<file:97f7af84-4e89-43d0-85bd-be5896fd8497>)

Once added, the check preview immediately plots the raw channel, and assigns an alphabetical variable name to the new channel. 

![Untitled](file:9216d365-5ffb-4f25-984b-6f83c23d04c8)

### **Transforming a time series channel**

Let‚Äôs rename this channel to ‚ÄúClimb Rate‚Äù and click the **Add Transform** area underneath the check preview. 

![Untitled](<file:aee6c381-daf3-406d-b703-58b25f2c15e4>)

First, we‚Äôll deduplicate timestamps in our run, then add a derivate transform to get the rate of change of our aircraft‚Äôs altitude, and then take a rolling aggregate.

![Untitled](file:4a35f44a-af41-417f-9d02-a1429b1262b9)

Once we‚Äôve added transforms, we see the derived time series highlighted in the preview area, with the original raw channel faded in the background.

In this editor, you can change transform parameters, such as the time window of a rolling aggregate.

![Untitled](<file:bd0047d0-8671-4b72-9594-1da162b27c19>)

### **Reordering transforms**

You can also change the order in which your transforms execute by dragging and dropping them into place. Drag a transform up to push it forward in execution order, or down to push it back.

## ‚öñÔ∏è¬†Creating a condition variable

In the section above, we defined a variable that functions as a derived time series channel. These channels can be compared to thresholds to produce conditions, the building blocks of checks.

![Untitled](<file:28a0c1da-93d3-4b98-9b78-d069356c9c10>)

You can create variables that are conditions themselves directly. Let‚Äôs create a condition called ‚ÄúLevel flight‚Äù that is active while our Climb Rate is within a threshold.

![Untitled](<file:8fcc232f-5730-4c07-8add-ad235571175d>)

After selecting **Create condition,** we select an existing variable (Climb Rate) from which to start building our condition. Once selected, we see a chart preview comparing our channel to a default threshold of 0.

![Untitled](<file:86d3ce6b-ca68-4955-94ad-a0717036076e>)

We define ‚ÄúLevel flight‚Äù as when the climb rate is in the range of 5 feet per second. This is condition has two sub-conditions, one for the upper threshold and one for the lower.

![Untitled](<file:a4319a81-b175-4973-bd58-93d21b44088b>)

Our highlight ranges update automatically, and our condition variable is ready to use.

### **Examining and replacing variables in conditions**

Click the time series button to the right of any condition variable to open an options menu. From here, you can **replace** the variable, or **jump to its definition,** which opens the variable builder where  the variable was constructed.

![Untitled](<file:e7fc0a6d-7945-4de1-bd2b-010574d63cad>)

### **Transforming raw channels in conditions**

If the channel you‚Äôre using in a condition is a raw channel, not a variable, you‚Äôll instead see the option to **transform** the variable, which opens a side editor.

![Untitled](<file:bd942c81-28df-41f7-a10a-f6df4920f662>)

This side editor allows in-place modification of the time series channel, allowing you to preview the result overlaid on the raw channel and update the condition to use the derived channel instead.

![Untitled](<file:0fbcde6e-be84-46e5-b3fd-cd105cd067de>)

Clicking the selected channel box, now labeled, ‚ÄúTransform of [time series channel]‚Äù, closes the side editor.

### üåü¬†Promoting a condition to a variable

If you‚Äôve defined a condition  to be used across checks, you can create a variable that represents that condition. 

![Untitled](<file:a218b84c-4675-40e6-be5a-0cc0b326cd63>)

Clicking the box icon to the right of any condition, labeled **Promote condition to a variable**, immediately creates a new variable for the condition. 

![Untitled](<file:21cd0bf5-8225-4211-81c1-c4f251192511>)

This condition is given an alphabetical name by default. You can change this name for clarity, and promote other conditions to a variable too. The variable description states the channel and threshold for simple checks.

![Untitled](<file:189bbce1-4347-401e-a194-cb8780b7ab1e>)

## üìê¬†Creating a formula variable

In addition to creating variables from raw or derived channels, variables can also be defined as formulas operating on other time series variables.

![Untitled](<file:13d94414-6e34-4215-acb8-a13057f7a243>)

In the formula editor, define an arithmetic expression of a time series using pre-existing time series variables. ****

![Untitled](<file:e75841d1-2698-41fd-8af7-eac2bb839e04>)

The formula editor has an **expression editor** on the left side of the form, and a list of **variable mappings** on the right. Use the highlighted alphabetical variable name to build your expression.

For this example, we want to compare elevator stick position (e) and pitch change rate (f), so our formula is just `e-f`. 

Clicking **Add formula** creates a new variable. The chart preview for that variable shows the source time series above the result. You can then add more transforms on top of this formula if needed.

![Untitled](<file:c9045c02-c68c-479f-b47d-28b240df4992>)

## Applying a checklist across multiple channels

A common pattern in test and evaluation is to apply the same check across multiple time series channels, with the same logic. To do this in Nominal, click the button underneath the check definition that says **Apply check to other channels**.

![Untitled](<file:81702915-fcd6-43ba-8fbf-94d100f752a4>)

A new box appears above the check definition containing one column for each time series channel or variable used in the definition. Each row represents a combination of time series against which the check will evaluate.

![Untitled](<file:3a324e40-3a54-4912-955b-ec4b6fa5eb04>)

Add more channels to evaluate by clicking the **+ button** next for the channel column. 

![Untitled](<file:860c3af7-9d29-4ea9-b379-fb7a2132c020>)

In the example above, we add more altitude check channels to evaluate for the ‚ÄúB‚Äù part of the condition, while keeping the ‚ÄúA‚Äù condition channel the same in every instance of the check.

![Untitled](<file:eca8c5b2-ed09-4814-ae24-4429205467ee>)

Since every row represents an instance of the check with different variables powering each condition, you can replace the channels in any column and any row.

## ‚öôÔ∏è¬†Setting condition persistence criteria

Nominal lets you define persistence criteria for any condition, whereby a check *only* fires if the condition lasts for more than some number of data points, or some period of time. 

By default, a condition does not have point or time persistence, and fires instantly when the violation condition is met. 

![Untitled](<file:35a4b639-62e7-4c05-88c2-7593236e3ac7>)

You can also configure how you want the violation ranges, highlighted in red on the time series chart, displayed on checks that use persistence criteria.

 By default, the violation range includes the entire duration when the condition is met. You can optionally trim this range to only include the time period *after* persistence criteria is also met.

---

---
title: Performing data review
description: Nominal is the leading platform for collaborative test data review.
sidebar:
  order: 6
---

## How data review works

Data review in Nominal is the process of:

1. applying a checklist to a run
2. reviewing time ranges where a check was violated
3. determining if the violation (a) should be **ignored** or (b) requires **further action**. 

A data review is complete when all violations have been reviewed. This section walks through how to apply checklists to runs, see and filter violations, and review them.

## Applying a checklist to a run

To apply a checklist to a run, navigate to the **runs section** of Nominal ([click here](https://app.gov.nominal.io/runs)) and select a run you‚Äôd like to review. This opens the **run details page.**

On the run details page, navigate to the **Checklists** tab. Here, you can apply a checklist to the run and kick off a data review.

[https://www.loom.com/share/f76fc0715beb46feb875072a8adf72e9](https://www.loom.com/share/f76fc0715beb46feb875072a8adf72e9)

Click ‚ÄúApply Checklist‚Äù to open a list of checklists against which you want to evaluate the run. Once selected, the new checklist(s) will appear in the list. Depending on the size of the run, and the complexity of the validations, you might need to wait for checklist execution to finish. 

Once execution is done, you should see a count of **violations** ‚Äî periods of time when a check triggered on the given run ‚Äî across all checks in the checklist. At this point, you and your team are ready to begin data review. 

[https://www.loom.com/share/ff919dbc89b04040a9ba1167f65c3710](https://www.loom.com/share/ff919dbc89b04040a9ba1167f65c3710)

## Handling checklist execution errors

See the status of any data review from the Checklists ****tab of the given run. 

A run must contain the input channels used to build a check, or else execution of the check will error, and will appear as such on the run page. 

![Untitled](<file:a393ac97-b704-4c44-8e2d-c507681cf281>)

Sometimes this error occurs because a checklist is applied to the wrong type of run, but it can also occur if there‚Äôs smaller deviation in channel names between runs, if the channels are used to create checks.

In the example above, some checks completed, but some failed because underlying channels were missing in the run.

## Reviewing automated violations

Once you‚Äôve applied a checklist to a run and execution completes, navigate to the **Violations** tab to see all automated check violations. These are items worth examining in your data review.

![Untitled](<file:8478d22a-cc9b-4bd8-a7f7-5901329b81e2>)

Click on any individual row to pull up more details about the check violation:

- The violation‚Äôs review status
- The violation‚Äôs start time and duration
- The triggering check & its priority
- The check‚Äôs pre-conditions

You can quickly move between check violations with the **up and down arrows** in the top right of the panel.

## Organizing check violations

You can apply as many checks as you want, and any check can trigger many times over the course of a run. The list of violations can get long quickly, so we offer several ways to filter. Filtering by checklist or by check is a quick way to find violations in question.

![Untitled](<file:c65d928f-9013-4fec-97b8-963aacad239e>)

You can see how much you‚Äôve narrowed the search space by checking the number of check violations filtered, underneath the filter group.

![Screenshot 2023-12-20 at 10.38.16 PM.png](file:4a5c4f36-4326-47e9-a5ee-3f69b0ed8d00)



## Creating a workbook from a check violation

From the violation review panel, you can click **‚ÄúCreate workbook‚Äù** in the top right of the panel to open a new notebook that constructs the violating check, applies it to the run, and centers the view on the failing check violation. All channels used to construct the check also populate. ## Update review status

By examining the check violation in the notebook view and consulting with colleagues, you can gather context about why the check violation triggered. To proceed with data review, you‚Äôll want to decide if you should **ignore** the violation, or if it **requires further action,** and add a note with your reasoning.

![Untitled](<file:0fe65ef7-d048-4b6c-8eda-c9ba9ba4997f>)

In some situations, you might want to ignore a check violation, but in other situations, the same failing check could be quite serious. For this reason, **individual check violations, not check rules, are the artifact of data review** in Nominal.
